					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/scruffy" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1203060); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1203060&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164759" alt="Scruffy" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1203060)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/scruffy" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1203060); return false;" >Scruffy</a></span> <span class="odate time_1318480152 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">13 Oct 2011 04:29</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1280146">
									

<p>Yet, even without the paraphernalia attached to either a government-oversight medical research area, or a university with a School of Medicine / Hospital attached, a lot of reasonably modern medical knowledge has been built on results of what is usually described as medical torture, perpetrated by individuals such as Mengele &amp; Wirths (Nazi regime), and Unit 731 of the Imperial Japanese Army.</p>
<p>Arguably, some of the testing logs use D-Class in a similar vein. A claim that the Foundation is at the &quot;forefront of medical research&quot; would essentially only be marketing spin, given that the Foundation deals entirely with objects/entities/effects that are outside of the normal course of human experience.</p>
<p>It isn't a bad 'orientation' style article. The last line about the top-hat guy seems a bit irrelevant though.</p>

							</div>

								
